    <div class="section" id="tools">
      <div class="section-label">01 ‚Äî Your Arsenal</div>
      <h2 class="section-title">Pick the Right Tool for the Job</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">Calvin switches tools every few months as the landscape evolves. Here's what each does best right now, and when to reach for which one.</p>
      <div class="tools-grid">
        <div class="tool-card claude">
          <div class="tool-name">Claude Code</div>
          <div class="tool-tag">Daily Driver ‚Ä¢ CLI</div>
          <div class="tool-desc">Splits tasks across <strong>sub-agent context windows</strong> (Haiku scouts the file system). Best-in-class at context engineering. Feels like "flying through the code." Access your dev DB, prod DB, and full local env.</div>
          <span class="strength">Context splitting</span><span class="strength">Frontend</span><span class="strength">Rails / Ruby</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-card codex">
          <div class="tool-name">Codex CLI</div>
          <div class="tool-tag">Long-Running Jobs ‚Ä¢ Sandbox</div>
          <div class="tool-desc">Periodic <strong>compaction</strong> after each turn ‚Äî can run for very long sessions. RL-fine-tuned on coding tasks. Excels at debugging complex concurrency & multi-service issues.</div>
          <span class="strength">Long sessions</span><span class="strength">Python monorepos</span><span class="strength">Concurrency bugs</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-card cursor">
          <div class="tool-name">Cursor</div>
          <div class="tool-tag">IDE-First ‚Ä¢ Semantic Search</div>
          <div class="tool-desc">Embeds your codebase for <strong>semantic retrieval</strong>. Fast new model. Good bug bot for code review. Great when you want to stay in your IDE and visually inspect code.</div>
          <span class="strength">IDE workflow</span><span class="strength">Code review bot</span><span class="strength">Fast iteration</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-card stack">
          <div class="tool-name">Deploy Stack</div>
          <div class="tool-tag">Minimize Boilerplate</div>
          <div class="tool-desc">Use <strong>Vercel, Next.js, Cloudflare Workers</strong> ‚Äî pre-built plumbing means agents deal with ~100‚Äì200 lines of focused code instead of service discovery & config hell.</div>
          <span class="strength">Vercel</span><span class="strength">Next.js</span><span class="strength">CF Workers</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section" id="comparison">
      <div class="section-label">01b ‚Äî Head to Head</div>
      <h2 class="section-title">Tool Comparison Matrix</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">A side-by-side breakdown to help you pick the right agent for the job at hand.</p>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table class="compare-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th class="feature-col">Feature</th>
              <th><span class="th-dot" style="background:var(--accent-cyan);box-shadow:0 0 8px var(--accent-cyan)"></span> Claude Code</th>
              <th><span class="th-dot" style="background:var(--accent-green);box-shadow:0 0 8px var(--accent-green)"></span> Codex CLI</th>
              <th><span class="th-dot" style="background:var(--accent-orange);box-shadow:0 0 8px var(--accent-orange)"></span> Cursor</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td class="feature-col">Interface</td>
              <td>CLI (Terminal)</td>
              <td>CLI (Sandbox)</td>
              <td>IDE (VS Code fork)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="feature-col">Context Strategy</td>
              <td><span class="cell-tag cyan-tag">Sub-agent splitting</span></td>
              <td><span class="cell-tag green-tag">Periodic compaction</span></td>
              <td><span class="cell-tag orange-tag">Semantic embeddings</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="feature-col">Search Method</td>
              <td>grep / ripgrep</td>
              <td>grep / ripgrep</td>
              <td>Vector embeddings</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="feature-col">Best For</td>
              <td>Daily coding, frontend, context-heavy tasks</td>
              <td>Long-running jobs, deep debugging, Python monorepos</td>
              <td>IDE-first workflows, quick edits, visual inspection</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="feature-col">Session Length</td>
              <td>Medium ‚Äî clear at ~50%</td>
              <td>Very long ‚Äî 24-48hr jobs</td>
              <td>Short-medium ‚Äî per-file focus</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="feature-col">Env Access</td>
              <td><span class="cell-yes">‚úì</span> Full local (DB, prod, queues)</td>
              <td><span class="cell-no">‚úó</span> Sandboxed by default</td>
              <td><span class="cell-partial">~</span> IDE scope only</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="feature-col">Code Review</td>
              <td>Via external bots</td>
              <td><span class="cell-yes">‚úì</span> Built-in, strong correctness</td>
              <td><span class="cell-yes">‚úì</span> Bug bot built-in</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="feature-col">Language Strength</td>
              <td>Ruby/Rails, Frontend, JS</td>
              <td>Python, monorepos (OpenAI-shaped)</td>
              <td>Broad ‚Äî follows IDE context</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="feature-col">Superpower</td>
              <td class="super-cell cyan-glow">Context splitting across sub-agents</td>
              <td class="super-cell green-glow">RL-trained persistence on hard bugs</td>
              <td class="super-cell orange-glow">Fast semantic search in IDE</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="feature-col">Weakness</td>
              <td>Context decay at 50%+ tokens</td>
              <td>Sandbox limits real env access</td>
              <td>Less freedom than CLI agents</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section" id="architecture">
      <div class="section-label">02 ‚Äî Under the Hood</div>
      <h2 class="section-title">How the Two Architectures Differ</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">Claude Code and Codex take fundamentally different approaches to managing context and long-running work. Understanding this helps you pick the right tool for the task.</p>
      <div class="arch-grid">
        <div class="arch-card">
          <h3><span class="dot cyan"></span> Claude Code</h3>
          <div class="flow">
            <span class="node cyan-bg">User prompt</span> ‚Üí
            <span class="node cyan-bg">Spawn N sub-agents</span> ‚Üí
            <span class="node cyan-bg">Explore via grep</span> ‚Üí
            <span class="node cyan-bg">Summarize back</span> ‚Üí
            <span class="node cyan-bg">Act on merged context</span>
          </div>
          <div class="detail">
            <span>‚ú¶</span> Each sub-agent gets its own clean context window<br>
            <span>‚ú¶</span> Uses grep (not embeddings) ‚Äî works great because code is context-dense<br>
            <span>‚ú¶</span> Respects .gitignore automatically
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="arch-card">
          <h3><span class="dot green"></span> Codex CLI</h3>
          <div class="flow">
            <span class="node green-bg">User prompt</span> ‚Üí
            <span class="node green-bg">Execute in sandbox</span> ‚Üí
            <span class="node green-bg">Compact after each turn</span> ‚Üí
            <span class="node green-bg">Continue indefinitely</span> ‚Üí
            <span class="node green-bg">Token % moves up/down</span>
          </div>
          <div class="detail">
            <span>‚ú¶</span> Designed for long-running 24‚Äì48hr jobs<br>
            <span>‚ú¶</span> RL-trained: emits complex grep expressions, writes scripts to modify filesystem<br>
            <span>‚ú¶</span> "AlphaGo-like" alien but effective behavior
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section" id="context">
      <div class="section-label">03 ‚Äî Critical Warning</div>
      <h2 class="section-title">The "Dumb Zone" ‚Äî Context Poisoning</h2>
      <div class="warning-banner">
        <div class="warning-icon">‚ö†Ô∏è</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Quality Degrades After ~50% Token Usage</h3>
          <p>Calvin actively clears context whenever token usage crosses <span class="mono">~50%</span>. The model in a poisoned context is like a student with 5 minutes left on an exam ‚Äî it panics and output quality drops sharply.</p>
          <div class="canary">
            <strong>üê§ The Canary Trick</strong><br>
            Plant a random fact at the start of your session ‚Äî <em>"My name is Calvin. I drank tea at 8am."</em><br>
            Periodically quiz the model. When it forgets ‚Üí your context is poisoned ‚Üí time to clear and restart.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section" id="tips">
      <div class="section-label">04 ‚Äî The Playbook</div>
      <h2 class="section-title">10 Tips to Become a Top 1% User</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">These are the patterns that separate casual users from the people shipping 5x more work per day.</p>
      <div class="tips-grid">
        <div class="tip-card"><div class="tip-num">01</div><div class="tip-content"><h3>Tests First, Always</h3><p>Gary ran 3 days without tests, then hit <span class="hl">100% coverage in 1 day</span> and "sped up like crazy." Agent output quality jumps dramatically when it can verify its own work.</p></div></div>
        <div class="tip-card"><div class="tip-num">02</div><div class="tip-content"><h3>Clear Context at 50%</h3><p>Don't let the agent spiral. When token usage crosses <span class="hl">~50%</span>, reset. A poisoned context window produces increasingly worse output.</p></div></div>
        <div class="tip-card"><div class="tip-num">03</div><div class="tip-content"><h3>Keep Codebases Small</h3><p>Target <span class="hl">100‚Äì200 lines</span> per focused package. Use microservices. Less plumbing = better agent performance.</p></div></div>
        <div class="tip-card"><div class="tip-num">04</div><div class="tip-content"><h3>Let Agents Check Their Work</h3><p>Lint, CI, test suites ‚Äî the more <span class="hl">automated verification loops</span> you give agents, the better their output. Code review bots on every PR.</p></div></div>
        <div class="tip-card"><div class="tip-num">05</div><div class="tip-content"><h3>Think Like a Manager</h3><p>Top users <span class="hl">direct flows</span>, kick off parallel tasks, review results, and context-switch. You're the architect; agents are your build crew.</p></div></div>
        <div class="tip-card"><div class="tip-num">06</div><div class="tip-content"><h3>Use the 10-Minute Pockets</h3><p>No more 4-hour blocks needed. <span class="hl">Kick off a task between meetings</span>, let it run, review later. The maker-vs-manager divide is dissolving.</p></div></div>
        <div class="tip-card"><div class="tip-num">07</div><div class="tip-content"><h3>Give It Real Environment Access</h3><p>CLI agents can access your <span class="hl">dev DB, production DB, job queues</span>. Gary debugged nested delayed jobs 5 levels deep ‚Äî agent found the bug and wrote a test.</p></div></div>
        <div class="tip-card"><div class="tip-num">08</div><div class="tip-content"><h3>Run Code Review Aggressively</h3><p>Use <span class="hl">multiple review bots</span>: Reptil for correctness, Cursor bug bot for speed, Codex for deep review.</p></div></div>
        <div class="tip-card"><div class="tip-num">09</div><div class="tip-content"><h3>Prototype ‚Üí Production Pipeline</h3><p>Write <span class="hl">quick in-memory prototypes</span>, then tell the agent to make it production-ready. Validate ideas fast.</p></div></div>
        <div class="tip-card"><div class="tip-num">10</div><div class="tip-content"><h3>Keep Tinkering ‚Äî It Changes Monthly</h3><p>Calvin switches tools <span class="hl">every few months</span>. The people who benefit most are constantly pushing the boundary.</p></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section" id="strengths">
      <div class="section-label">05 ‚Äî Know Your Agent</div>
      <h2 class="section-title">Superpowers vs. Pitfalls</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">Understanding what agents excel at and where they fall short is the difference between 10x productivity and hours wasted.</p>
      <div class="sw-grid">
        <div class="sw-card super">
          <h3>‚ú¶ Agent Superpowers</h3>
          <div class="sw-item"><span class="icon">‚ö°</span><span><strong>Relentless persistence</strong> ‚Äî they never stop trying</span></div>
          <div class="sw-item"><span class="icon">‚ö°</span><span><strong>Codebase exploration</strong> ‚Äî grep through thousands of files in seconds</span></div>
          <div class="sw-item"><span class="icon">‚ö°</span><span><strong>Complex grep expressions</strong> ‚Äî emit patterns that would "torture a human"</span></div>
          <div class="sw-item"><span class="icon">‚ö°</span><span><strong>Deep debugging</strong> ‚Äî trace issues across nested job queues & services</span></div>
          <div class="sw-item"><span class="icon">‚ö°</span><span><strong>Rapid prototyping</strong> ‚Äî full working demo in minutes</span></div>
          <div class="sw-item"><span class="icon">‚ö°</span><span><strong>Concurrency handling</strong> ‚Äî decent at spotting race conditions</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="sw-card weak">
          <h3>‚öë Watch Out For</h3>
          <div class="sw-item"><span class="icon">üö©</span><span><strong>Code duplication</strong> ‚Äî they "make more of whatever's there"</span></div>
          <div class="sw-item"><span class="icon">üö©</span><span><strong>Context poisoning</strong> ‚Äî goes down wrong path and doubles down</span></div>
          <div class="sw-item"><span class="icon">üö©</span><span><strong>Architecture smell</strong> ‚Äî still can't judge optimal system design</span></div>
          <div class="sw-item"><span class="icon">üö©</span><span><strong>Prompt injection</strong> ‚Äî vulnerable to untrusted input</span></div>
          <div class="sw-item"><span class="icon">üö©</span><span><strong>Training data bias</strong> ‚Äî works best on what resembles its training set</span></div>
          <div class="sw-item"><span class="icon">üö©</span><span><strong>Long-context decay</strong> ‚Äî quality drops past 50% token window</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section" id="quote">
      <div class="quote-card">
        <span class="quote-mark">"</span>
        <blockquote>I feel like I can do five people's worth of work in a single day. It's like rocket boosters. It's unbelievable.</blockquote>
        <div class="attr">‚Äî Gary Tan, YC President, on Claude Code</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section" id="mindset">
      <div class="section-label">07 ‚Äî The New Mindset</div>
      <h2 class="section-title">Who Benefits Most</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">The most productive users treat coding agents like a team of junior engineers ‚Äî giving them clear, scoped tasks, solid test coverage, and reviewing their output.</p>
      <div class="mindset-grid">
        <div class="mindset-card"><div class="emoji">üéØ</div><h4>Senior Engineers</h4><p>Can spot bad architecture, direct agents precisely, and turn quick ideas into shipped code with a few words.</p></div>
        <div class="mindset-card"><div class="emoji">üß†</div><h4>Manager-Brained Builders</h4><p>Excel at juggling 10 parallel tasks, reviewing outputs, and context-switching between branches.</p></div>
        <div class="mindset-card"><div class="emoji">üé®</div><h4>Designer-Artists</h4><p>Have taste for what belongs in the product. Can direct what stays and what goes ‚Äî the "what" over the "how."</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>

